Amend the European Stability Pact.
The European Stability Pact, which underpins the euro by imposing constraints determining the size of the budget deficits of the Union's members, is in danger.
Germany, the heavyweight of the Union, has failed to meet its budget commitments to its European partners.
Furthermore, she has used her political weight to cover up the warning signal of her deficit, set up by the European Commission in accordance with the terms of the European Stability Pact.
Today it's France who plays the bad boys.
The number two of the Union, not very enthusiastic, has now officially declared that he cannot keep his commitment to reducing the budget deficit, a year after the small Ireland received an official warning about its fiscal policies, despite its budget surpluses, and in a very severe manner.
Thus, four years after its signing, the European Stability Pact is a true disaster.
Thus, Europe seems to be very affected by the talks aiming to abolish it, as well as the talks aiming to amend it.
And rightly so: the pact is poorly designed and its implementation poorly done.
The limitation of the deficit to 3% of GDP is arbitrary and disregards the fact that deficits automatically increase when the economy slows down.
By admitting this fact, the architects of the pact have exacerbated the situation by adopting two poorly thought-out solutions.
They introduced a safety clause allowing any country to suspend its deficit limits in case of a significant recession, but they defined it in such a way that any suspension is virtually impossible in practice.
Worried that serious slowdowns could breach the deficit ceiling, they decreed that a normal deficit was equivalent to zero deficit.
Thus, each year, each country must submit a budget projection for the two years ahead demonstrating how the budget balance will be achieved in due time.
The German commitment for 2002 was made in 2001, when its economy was growing at a reasonable rate.
The unexpected slowdown prevents Germany from meeting its targets.
The finance minister, Hans Eichel, reasonably decided not to worsen the situation by adopting a fiscal policy of budget contraction.
The Commission, seeking to position itself as the guardian of the pact, wanted to issue a warning, but this decision had to be taken by real politicians, the Council of Finance Ministers.
No one wanted to embarrass Germany since everyone recognized they could face the same problem in the future.
Thus, no warning was issued.
The situation of France is different.
In election periods, politicians inevitably make promises, including reducing the tax burden.
In a country where the tax burden is significant, it's not just a matter of showing political intelligence, but also economic intelligence, as long as budgetary expenditures are also reduced.
However, in a country where everyone benefits from certain privileges funded by the state, budget cuts are definitely ill-received.
Thus, France cannot meet its targets and the Commission has expressed its frustration.
But France has mastered the art of defying the rules of the European Union.
Inevitable political maneuvers will follow.
Economists and cynics are hardly surprised.
The objective of the pact, to establish a fiscal discipline among countries sharing the same currency, is quite acceptable.
However, the loss of control over their national monetary policy, EU members now benefit from only one macroeconomic tool: fiscal policies.
The challenge is therefore to combine long-term discipline with short-term flexibility.
Like promising to go on a diet before a big party, this challenge is not easy to reconcile.
The European Stability Pact is too simplistic and technocratic: the 3% target set by the Brussels bureaucrats cannot bind politicians into compliance.
The solution must be found elsewhere.
Fortunately, we don't have to look too far.
The monetary policy faces the same challenge.
She must stabilize prices in the long term while remaining sufficiently flexible in the short term to manage economic cycles.
Over the past decade, monetary policy has achieved significant success.
The recipe is the same everywhere: it's enough to delegate this policy to a competent group, the Central Bank, granting it the necessary political independence and a clear and well-defined mandate.
Knowing that any mishaps will be resolved in the future, it's up to them to show some common sense.
This has been one of the major improvements in the monetary domain over the past few years.
The same approach should work for fiscal policy.
Some fear, of course, losing democracy in the process.
It is essential to understand that fiscal policy serves two very different purposes.
The first is structural and redistributive and concerns the importance of the budget and its detailed structure, both in terms of expenditures and revenues.
These decisions cannot be delegated and must remain in the hands of elected governments, subject to parliamentary approval and oversight.
The second is macroeconomic: it involves defining the budget balance to manage fluctuations in economic cycles.
It differs little from monetary policy and can be delegated to an independent body.
Thus, the task of Europe is clear.
Each country must regain full control of its fiscal policies but delegate its macroeconomic components, its decisions on deficits or surpluses, to an independent Fiscal Policy Committee whose long-term objective is the stabilization (or reduction, for certain countries) of public debt.
For this to be achieved, the status of such a Committee and its mandates must be subject to a consensus within the European Union, without any interference from Brussels, without any arbitrary regulations, without any political decision-making, but simply relying on common sense.
